content: Still useful, but needs updating. Has been abandoned.

not user friendly..it took me forever to find search feature and it is several steps each time to get to it...when I DO click on subscribe it is several more steps to add to catagories and when I did a help search it was all about the ones who make the podcast not the feature. refunded

*WAS* best I had tried years ago. Unfortunately, abandoned since 2018/ish and completely broken on newest Android 11. Seek a newer app that is still supported. (I went for Podcast Republic, but there are many options.) Unfortunate, because I really liked this app.

I use this 10 hours a day. The BEST podcatcher option available on any platform. worth every cent. Needs device to device sync and UI overhaul for simplicity Edit : no longer supported. Abandoned by dev. Can't find anything better but this app has become unstable. Avoid.

DON'T BUY!! WAS good before, now abandoned by dev... I was forced to use an iPhone by my employer so I couldn't use the app for the last few years, finally able to use Android again only to find out my podcast player I PAID FOR is wonky because the developer is MIA. If that's really the case then this needs pulled down off the catalog, I'll give the dev a few days to respond before reporting the app.
Couldn't survive driving without doggcatcher

Recently Doggcatcher has become buggy. Episodes will stop randomly. More concerning are the ads that are clipped into episodes seemingly at random. This is a dealbreaker for me. Previous review: This is one of the most used applications on my phone. Outstanding product. They've done a great job updating it with new features.
Used to be the best podcast app on the Google Store. It hasn't been updated or changed for years now.
After 8 years I still think this is the best app I've ever downloaded. Seemless, endlessly customisable, connects to everything I need it to. Still give it 5 stars.
Pauses frequently for no reason during playing of episodes

I used to use this app all the time; it was my go to podcast app. I am however moving on because the app really is not maintained all that much anymore and it does not provide any cross device synchronization capabilities. This used to be a 5 star app, but it's been mothballed.

I've used this app for years. It was my most used app, seriously. I've really loved it until the devoloper stopped updating it back in 2018. A thread on the devoloper's site mentions that theres no immediate plans for updates & they don't have a future plan as for where to go with the app. It still works on android OS 10. (As of this review) But its becoming fairly buggy since the devoloper isn't maintaining it. If a doggcatch 2 is ever released, I'll bite. In the mean time I'm moving on.
Was great but now is riddled with bugs including playback, queues, and downloads.
Why does this app need permission to make phone calls?
This was the best podcast player I have used for the android OS. It is no longer being updated and has multiple glitches and problems.

Not a lot of bells and whistles. But that's OK. All I do is subscribe and listen to the downloaded episodes. When there are multiple podcasts to listen to, I have it set to play in the order of their release dates. Simple and easy.

This used to be the best podcast app out there. Now it crashes, the controls do not work properly, podcasts stop unexpectedly. I have to always open it twice as it does not load correctly....please fix!
Any plans to support podcast 2.0 features?

Love it..I've tried others and this one's the best I have not had any trouble with the updates or any of the other things mentioned using a Google Pixel 3A. A long time ago I had a feature request and emailed their tech and the next day the feature was on the app...

This used to be a 4-star app. It had its random glitches but I was able to overcome these issues. As time goes by, this app becomes less functional. I have paid for this app for its features and convenience but now it is unusable. Specifically, it tries to re-download podcast episodes which are already in my Playlist and it does so when the app refreshes, which it does often. If you happen to be listening to a podcast when it refreshes, the podcast will end abruptly but then delete itself.
How can something free be so good? Thank you DoggCatcher.
No updates, performance meh, Still use it but I'm not happy as I was 3 years ago when I got it.

Super customizable- can control what is downloaded and what isn't, stream or download, saving locations, & useful categorization. It can draw from RSS & websites. Doesn't seem to be limited in what it can find and play. Oh- and it does video, too. Really pleased. I was relying on limited queues from Stitcher before this. Definitely a worthwhile upgrade for under $5! EDIT: Needs an update badly. Lots of crashing issues, often forced to drop/resubscribe to feeds to get them to load, etc.
Simple, easy to control, reliable and most importantly, NO ADS! Download on wifi, play in background, feed diagnostics and cleanup. Been using it for over three years, no problems.
Abandoned. Time to move on to something new.

Was the best podcast player for over 5 years I have been using it. Now comes up blank when opening. Does not autoplay next episodes. Way too buggy now. Need to find something else if issues are no longer being fixed.

content: Often randomly plays a different podcast to the one you're trying to listen to.

If you want the controls, you have to let the app interrupt you when they want to promote something. 2) Audio playback cuts out at random. You are forced to pull the app back up and hit play. Awesome. Does everything I need for listening to podcasts. (Was 4 stars now 1 star) 9-24-2020 Take that back. It stops after every episode. I have set it to auto play the next episode but after the last update it stops after each podcast. Fix this please, soon.
Great app... But the share feature is wonky. I just want a link, not a 50 page dissertation on it. Seriously... The title of the podcast and a link is all we need!

Works great for me, been using for 5 years or more.

A full featured podcaster. Love it.

Used to be the best podcast app on the market but is now abandonware. No updates for a year or two mean bugs are mounting up. Have switched to Podcast Addict which is excellent.
Great app. Been using this app for years with no issues.

What happened to this app? Been using since '09 and it was great, but now i have to "create a playlist" to get each episode to autoplay??? It's crashing a ton, tells me my playlist is empty when it's not, tells me there's no downloaded episodes when there are. It's just the point where it's no longer useful at all. ---------ADDED COMMMENTS ------ 25-Apr-2019: Still using DoggCatcher! Four years +/-. Still hoping for browser based config/playing, cross-device coordination (listen once, show as done everywhere..), and some way to participate in podcast reviewing: Podcasters refer to links in art that take us to source server review UI (the podcast's review page at Sketcher, for instance).But, not supported. Otherwise, still a good straightforward app, and I'll probably keep using it. Worth every penny.

And please add an ability to shuffle a group of podcasts (or a playlist)...so much good content out there and so little time.
Grateful for the years of excellent functionality, but it's been nearly a year and a half since the last update. Time to move on.

Excellent. Use it every day

I've been using DoggCatcher for many years, and was loving it until recently, but now I'm having a couple of issues that are so annoying that I'm looking at downloading a new podcast app. First of all, the podcasts skip a lot during playback. I had this problem months ago, but they must've fixed it because it stopped doing it. Now it's doing it again. It happens on all my episodes across multiple podcasts, so I know it's not the quality of the individual recordings. Secondly, as soon as I open the app, a notification shows that "DoggCatcher is busy updating [insert podcast name here]". However, that notification stays there until you force close the app. I saw it one night before I went to bed and it was still there the next morning. I'm very disappointed after being a loyal user for so many years.
Great podcatcher (free and paid versions) with powerful options.

The permission request to make phone calls doesn't strikes me as necessary and the fact that the apps push hard in a spammy way to get you to enable it doesn't look good. Not implying that the app is nefarious, just pointing out the fact that the explanation for it don't satisfy me in this day and age where privacy invasions are the news of the day. It's main competitor can provide the same functionality of pausing and resuming with only the storage access permission requested. The functionality of this app it's ok and well thought otherwise.
I've loved this app for years. It is the best app that I ever purchased. I highly recommend.

There is n email address within the app for support, absurd for a paid podcast app. Finally, DC does poor job of displaying more than a token number of the 1,000s out there. After downloading a 46mb podcast to what I hoped was a folder on the SD card, it disappeared somewhere on my device. I gave up, took the $ loss, and uninstalled it. Developer never answered email.

The new UI is quite beautiful and I'm liking the constant updates. Still need a better looking widget though. April 2012- new amazing looking widget and icon. To this is what app perfection looks like. May 31st 2019 - Uninstalled Unfortunately I had to. The app became far to buggy and began crashing other apps. I'll miss the UI, style and ease of use. Good by old friend. No updates in a year...

Samsung Galaxy S8+ w/Android Pie is completely incompatible with this app now. Best app for android.

Relatively easy to use and reliable. Wish I could adjust the feed option to occur 15 mins after the hour rather than be forced to do them on the hour as news feeds typically upload 10-15 minutes after broadcast.

Long time user. I've tried changing to other podcast players but always. one back to Doggcatcher. I've used this app since Android 1.5, and I've never seen the developer let a problem like this go unaddressed for so long.

It's a great app for playing podcasts. However, there a few too many bugs that need to be fixed. 1) Podcasts will randomly pause playback. Hitting play will start it again, but it rewinds back and replays some of what you've already heard. This can fix playback for a little awhile, but it will pause again after a random number of minutes. 2) Downloads/Updating never stops. Once you open the app, it will begin to check for updates and download new episodes. Once complete, the notification will remain and never finish. 3) The Pause/Play button on the notification drop down and on the lock screen will only display a pause button after the app has been running for awhile. It will still do both pause and play actions, but it will always appear as a pause button. Annoying bugs when you're using an app you paid for.

**update** On my new Honor phone with most recent Android software, I can't listen to podcasts without the phone restarting. Tried troubleshooting some but no resolution yet. Had to lower from 5 stars. This review has been revised for the performance and user experience bugs I've experienced on 9.0 Pie. The app randomly pauses/stops playing and needs a force restart. This usually happens after about 30 min of play time. When using Bluetooth if the headphones are connected to two devices it will not play even after force closing the app. The only fix is to re-pair the headphones. When playing in a car stereo system it will pause the podcast when jumping 30 seconds ahead. These bugs are making the app near unusable. Please test the app on new versions of Android before they release to ensure the app is compatible. If these issues aren't fixed within a month I'll be switching to a more reliable podcast player.
Interface can be a bit busy at times but provides many needed features lacking in other apps.

If you own a Toyota you may have issues with skip ahead/back where the audio is paused after using steering wheel controls to perform these functions. I switched to Pocket Casts to get around this after it annoying me for years.

I didnt use any podcast management apps prior to using Dogg Catcher (downloaded at recommendation of a friend), but I have been very happy with this app. I have never had an issue finding an downloading a podcast, even smaller more obscure ones. I can set the playlist and listen without taking breaks to change tracks or search for the next one I want to listen to. Great for when I'm driving or at work. I also just like the overall look of the app and like how the library is organized. My only complaint is the progress bar is right above the play/pause/ff/rw buttons so I sometimes skip ahead in the podcast when I'm trying to pause or ff/rw.

This feature saves you so much time, 8.5 hours in 2 months on Podcast Addict, but without it, I can't recommend this app.

This is a very strong podcasting app. I've used it daily for more than 5 years and it is still the best I can find.    Unfortunately help requests are auto-rejected and never reach the dev unless you "escalate' your own email request after sending it and then overcome the representatives who automatically assume every problem is user error.  Not surprisingly bugs persist.     The most visible bug is that it constantly shows a "downloading" notification which cannot be stopped or removed, which persists even when there is no internet signal to 'download' from.     A friend of mine installed it on my recommendation and uninstalled right away when it was always using her system resources 'downloading' and she couldn't stop it.     Also it's SD card storage access is very restricted and occasionally problematic.

When Dogg Catcher works, it works well. The problem is it won't stop working when it's supposed to be idle. I'll be listening to a book on Audible, or watching a video, and DC will suddenly wake up and start playing. Over and over I have to stop DC and start the desired app.
If it worked it would be great.

The minute past the hour when this app updates is fixed at :00 and as far as I know it cannot be changed. The top of the hour is a disastrous time to insist on updating. This app monopolizes your WiFi for a good minute or so when it updates, and if you're doing anything time critical you will be out of luck till it's done. This means no Eventbrite tickets that go on sale at the top of the hour unless they don't sell out immediately, no quiz show participation, etc. It would maybe work for the updates to start at a random time when the WiFi is idle, or for updates to occur at a sufficiently low bandwidth / low priority that it doesn't squeeze other traffic out. This is just about my only beef with this app, otherwise it's really good.

replyContent:
You can do this by selecting a playlist that groups your episodes by feed.  The next button also picks from the current playlist so be sure you've got a playlist selected that has episodes in the order you want them to play.

content: I bought this and used it a number of years, but the developer quit improving it. I switched to Podcast Addict because it has the volume boost I was looking for.

Great app but showing it's age Still works well, and still handles password protected feeds the best. That being said, a number of modern features found in other apps are missing, such as a "new release" list that shows all the latest podcasts across all subscribed feeds before downloading the episodes & sorting into a playlist. Having to drill down into each feed individually to see new episodes now feels tedious & downright old-fashioned. Using the auto-download/auto-delete options in lieu of either seeing all new releases at once or feed by feed seems like a recipe for disaster without time-consuming micromanagement. Updating all feeds takes noticeably longer than other apps, presumably because it downloads the entire feed each time rather then just the delta. These missing features combined with no updates since June 2016 add up to an app in need of a refresh. Unless you subscribe to a lot of password protected feeds, there are better options available.

replyContent: That message means that another app on your device has taken the audio away from DoggCatcher.  This is what android does to make sure only one app is playing audio at a time.   We try to detect the more common apps that do this and display a message but there are lots out there that we aren't aware of yet.

replyContent: I would take a look at what is in the DoggCatcher folder on the SD card.  Anything DC downloads goes in there.  If there's less than 16GB in there, it's likely the Android is misreporting the usage.  That has happened in the past.  Please contact support and we'll try to help out - support at doggcatcher dot com

Pretty disappointing.  Upgraded to Doggcatcher from a free podcast manager that did most of what I wanted, hoping for a few extra customization options.  It has those in spades, but suffers from a few really basic nuisance behaviors.  First, there's no way to set it so that it streams episodes by default, rather than downloading (streaming requires use of a context menu).  And once it's streaming, it randomly pauses.  This is clearly a known issue, and various forum threads explain it as a problem of other apps requesting audio focus.  Frankly I don't care -- I've used at least two free programs and not encountered this behavior.  Finally, it refuses to stream some episodes with long names and/or unusual characters in their names that play smoothly in the other managers I've used.  Good for lots of detailed feed-specific options, but really disappointing for more general a la carte listening.
replyContent:
You can change to use streaming as the default in settings / audio player.  

Please contact support and let us know the name/url of the feeds you are having problems with and we'll take a look.  We do have an open bug around the special chars in filenames but don't have a feed to replicate the issue.

Thanks for the feedback.

ChromeCast Audio doesn't work.  Tried it on multiple devices and won't work for any.  Update:  DoggCatcher replied saying it must be my ChromeCast Audio fault.  Funny that it works it Play Music, QCast, and Pocket Cast.  Doesn't seem like good customer service.
replyContent:
Apps the integrate with ChromeCast basically point ChromeCast to the media file, so if there is missing audio, something is going wrong on ChromeCast itself. 

You can confirm that by trying out another app that uses ChromeCast, like YouTube or Netflix.

Thanks for the feedback.

content: This thing has features I didn't even know I needed. Best App Around!!!  Please add Roku support.

Update: 5/26/2015: I would love to add a star or two. But dev/s seem to work on features they want to implement, which is fine, that's their prerogative. I've made two feature requests that I think would greatly improve functionality. 1) Option to sort feeds alphabetically 2) ability to search episode titles and descriptions across all your feeds. No response from the DC folks. That's fine, but even a simple "not going to implement" would cause me to cough up another star.   As mentioned by others,  the UI is weird. But you get used to it.  I would give 4 stars, but I hated the feed list even before the switch to tiles (thanks to dev for putting list view back, though).  I don't understand why the feed list cannot be alphabetical per user preference. Drives me nuts.  There's a thread or two in the forums about this, but not at ton of dev interest/response.  Don't get me wrong, DC is one of my most used apps. And I would probably be a little more forgiving if it wasn't a $3 app.

I see from your responses to similar complaints regarding the long press change that you plan to implement multiple ep downloads soon. Not sure why there is an idea that multi episode download is a feature that warrants implementation at a priority and "ease of access" that long press provides, as opposed to making THAT feature an option under the 3 hamburger dot menu. For that matter, downloading multi eps wasn't even difficult the old way. I hope youll consider the feedback you're seeing and revert back.
replyContent:
Using the long press on episodes really is the only discover-able way to implement multi-select...that's how all the google apps implement it.  The multi-select will allow more functions than just downloading.  Also, next Friday's release will make the hamburger much easier to hit we'll avoid accidental downloads.

Thanks for the feedback.

The notification that is displayed when episodes are downloading is sort of required by android, otherwise android can kill the app and interrupt the downloads.  The most common use of this is for audio players, but it can be used for other things, like preventing download interruptions..

content: Only thing keeping me from giving it a 5 star rating is the interface. It's not bad by any means, but nothing special a little bland. Great app! Thanks

...with what looks like extensive documentation, would probably rate it higher if I read directions first instead of just muddling through on my own.  Only serious issue is it regularly freezes up on my Samsung Tracfone.  Hardware or software at fault, I csnnot say.

Good news is that the developer is very responsive.  The app flat-out works.  But please stop tinkering to change the display to follow the latest fads.  Could stand to have a better interface.  Good news is that all the controls are on the main page--unlike many competitors.  I recently bought Pocket Casts and compared it to DoggCatcher.  The DoggCatcher user interface is far superior to the gaudy look of Pocket Casts.  DoggCatcher tabular view is far superior.  Love the better settings control of DoggCatcher, too.  Pocket Casts wins on cloud sync and variable speed playback, though (DoggCatcher allows one custom variable speed above 1.5x, up to 2.0x, Pocket Casts allows anything up to 3.0x).  User interface and controls: DoggCatcher;  Syncing across devices: Pocket Casts;  Ability to customize settings: DoggCatcher;  Data Usage: Pocket Casts (updates only new feeds BUT "pull down to refresh" feature sucks, only results in unintentional updates and data usage);  Timeliness of podcast updates: DoggCatcher (because it checks all servers whenever you sync, unlike Pocket Casts);  Variable speed playback: Pocket Casts.
pros: - easy to use UI - easy to discover new content  cons: - glitchy on updates sometimes, currently my widget does not update properly - having to pay extra for variable speed is greedy

replyContent:
I think I may be honing in on the cause of this.  If you are willing to test out a custom build, I can probably get you one in the next couple of days.  Please contact support at doggcatcher dot com and I get you a build.

Thanks for keeping the pressure on about this one.  The fix is overdue.

Apps are required to display a notification when they are doing something that we don't want android to interrupt, like updating feeds. The app itself is amazing, no doubt about it, but it is lingering in the device memory forever even when having been inactive for long periods of time hogging memory and eating a bit of CPU time and draining your battery even though it should only be active while syncing (backend activity) and playback (frontend activity) fix this and 5 star for sure
one thing holds this back from 5 stars - I would like the ability to sync Podcasts across devices (phone & tablet) at least new vs played, though position would be great as well.

I once gave this app 5 stars and paid $5 for it.  Now in 2015 this is a 2 star app at best. Major issues:  1) portability across devices, and 2) storage management. For #1:  developers have had years to figure out how to easily port all the settings (and there are MANY including subscriptions) from one device to the next.  You need a CS degree from MIT to know how backup, zip, export the settings out of your old device, re-import back into the new device at the precise location, and hope they take on the new device.  Seriously, I dont know how the average person would even know where to start. For #2:  the default storage location is the  device memory, and on Lollipop it is not possible to just use the SD card.  If you try to move storage to the SD card, the app says all is OK, gives a green sign, but then it fails (it cannot use the SD card) and crashes.  I get it that Android has changed security and blah blah blah, but how long does it take for developers to include a pop up to a reference article, or something to help us out?  Why is storage - a KEY ITEM for the health of the device - stuck under the "Miscellaneous" menu as if its an afterthought??

DoggCatcher has always been my app of choice, but I must now abandon it. content: I'll echo what others have said: this isn't the easiest to use application I've come across, but there is an option for everything I've wanted. Once you have it set up, it is really easy to simply listen to your podcasts, though.  I originally selected DoggCatcher because of the variable playback speed (which is top-notch) and built-in sleep timer, but the application continues to impress me with its flexibility and continued development. It is also refreshingly free of "accounts" and "the cloud", simply serving as a solid podcast client. 3.5 stars.  I've been using DoggCatcher for many years now but only because the alternatives are worse.  Near perfect for UI and functionality  It wasn't too hard to figure out how to auto download podcasts and auto play them in more or less the right order.  In contrast other podcast app makers need to go back to user interface junior high.  DC also supports five button headsets.  Surprisingly other apps don't, and if you listen to podcasts in the car and skip programs frequently, three buttons simply isn't enough.  I subtract 0.5 stars here only because like other apps there are too many confusing options.  This is because the base UI still needs work and app makers put knobs everywhere to compensate since its easier than designing it properly.  -1 stars for support  DC has some glaring annoyances.   First it gets confused if two podcasts have the same name (?!?).  Second it randomly starts playing again after disconnecting from Bluetooth.  These have been around a long time and you sometimes get the feeling support doesn't want to hear about things that are hard to fix.  All in all, solid app but I'm still searching for perfect.

I bought this app as it came highly recommended on Lifehacker.  I also wanted to be able to play podcasts from local .mp3 files.  This is the "virtual feeds" feature in DoggCatcher.  In general the app looks nice, but I had several problems with virtual feeds.  The podcasts would play in the wrong order and by default the next episode didn't play automatically.  I couldn't quickly find out a way to sort the pod cast order based on mp3 filename.  Also switching between different feeds was confusing (e.g., if I select a feed 'A', play it, then navigate to feed 'B' and hit play again, playback will resume from 'A' and not 'B').  There are probably ways of getting these things done in DoggCatcher but I would expect this type of rather simple functionality to work out of the box without exploring advanced settings in the app.
replyContent:
The playback order of files is based on the audio playlist, rather than the last feed that you selected (this is different from itunes).  Feel free to contact support or post in our forums and we'll help you out.

Thanks for the feedback.

Unfortunately, Doggcatcher (paid version) is not that app.  On the plus side, it will play podcasts and it has variable speed settings.    Otherwise, its menu settings are more convoluted than intuitive.  It won't display all of an episode's description.  It had a hard time playing the chapters of my audiobook in order.  (Instead of playing "title 01", "title 02", "title 03", Doggcatcher kept trying to play "title 10" after each one of those episodes.)  The last straw was when the app last updated and deleted all of my feeds.    Ultimately, the app does not lend itself well to distraction-less driving or frustration-free podcast listening.

DoggCatcher makes it easy to manage dozens of podcast subscriptions. If you subscribe to over a dozen podcasts like I do, this is $5 very well spent.

I agree with another reviewer that a "favorites" selection would be nice.  I normally have the settings play one podcast at a time but it would be cool to have the option to play a list (Favorites) of podcasts concurrently at a time of my choosing.  This is the one feature that I miss about the Stitcher app.  But I don't always want all of my podcasts to play at once, just when my hands are tied when I'm doing dishes, building, or painting, etc.  That's my only suggestion.  Otherwise, this app is perfect.

Although this app has many rave reviews, most never talked about the important part of installing this on a Galaxy S4; it doesn't store downloads on the SD card. This really limits its usefulness.
replyContent: This limitation is due to the specific version of android that ships to the S4.  It does not allow any app to write to the SD card.  There doesn't seem to be a way around this at the moment but we're hoping Samsung will change this in the future.  It's the only device we're aware of that limits SD card writing this way.

Google Listen did both these things in a flawed but simple to use interface. I've yet to find anything that makes playing and maintaining podcasts as simple. I would love to see an app that appreciates space in a layout and simplicity in function.

Specifically after trying just about every setting combination it still constantly deletes videos I either haven't watched or are in the process of watching.  They seem to be deleted after they move off the feed list, but since it sometimes takes me weeks to watch a video I end up missing a lot.  Update: More recent updates have helped in this regard, you can set feeds so that they still display expired content.  Updated rating.
replyContent: Videos and audio will be deleted once they move off the feed list, otherwise we'd leave orphaned files on your device.  There are a couple things you can do...1 - increase the max items for the feed or 2 - enable pin expired (this will keep all episodes even after they are no longer in the feeds).  Thanks for supporting the app.

With the price of this app, I hold big expectations for its future.  It might be the best podcaster on the android market, but several glaring issues remain:  * When you unplug the headphones, your podcast doesn't stop as you've come to expect from android audio apps, instead it starts playing on the phone loudspeaker.  * Bluetooth support.  What Bluetooth Support?  Exactly.  All you get is play/pause.  No display of the currently playing episode.  No support for "next" or cueing.  This is a premium app and it's surprising that support is so poor.  Surely there's a large car commuting community with newer dashboards which connect via bluetooth.  * When you hit the "play" button on your headphones (or bluetooth play), DoggCatcher seems to always love to start playing, in preference over other audio apps you might have expected.
It all just works, and the interface makes sense. If more apps were of this quality, Android would be a better place.

While the UI may take some getting used to, and it's not the prettiest of the podcast apps (although it certainly is good-looking), Doggcatcher is more feature-packed than the rest, and, of your an avid podcast listener, worth your money.

I really wanted to organize my podcasts according to when I listen to each podcast, and manually order the podcasts on these lists. DoggCatcher ("DC") seems to be the pod-catcher that does this.  That said, I'd like DC even more if I could see the first line or two of the description of each podcast, as in Google Listen (this could be an option in both feeds and playlists; having to choose "description" from the menu for each episode is a slow way to hunt for content). And a way to set the "auto-delete episodes when they're done", to leave the most recent episode or two not deleted, so that one has a chance to rewind back into a podcast that has just finished.  Also, I would have liked more detail in documentation; where it says "User playlists can be configured to automatically add..." it would be nice to have details like "view your playlist and tap on the name to get the playlist menu; in this menu, tap on the triangle in the lower corner of your playlist's title to bring up a submenu with 'edit playlist', in which you can configure auto-add".  Still, this is a very nice app, 5/5. Users have no end of odd feature requests.

The blue them color is fine, but the light green is really ugly. The icon looks like the letters are supposed to be white, but it's in a selected state with a transparent green overlay. Another big problem is the abuse of notifications. There's no conceivable reason for a notification to tell me that I've left the app to view a link in the browser. I do recommend it, with my complaints as caveats.

The first night I downloaded and installed the app, I ended up using a large portion of my monthly data usage allowance on my plan. I got an alert from my carrier about this, and went into the app and changed the settings, telling it to only download feeds when the phone was connected to wi-fi, and to only download feeds when the phone was connected to a power source. I rarely use wi-fi, and only use a power source when the phone needs to be charged. From the time that I changed those settings up until tonight, the phone had not been on a power source, and I had not turned on wi-fi, but when I checked the phone, I found that the app was still downloading feeds. Until I can get a handle on why it was doing this even after I changed the settings and left wi-fi and the charger off )I verified that wi-fi on the phone was NOT activated), I can't trust the app. As the review title says, it could be user error. But I would think those 2 settings would be self explanatory, and would make the app behave the way you would expect it to with those 2 settings active. Apparently not.

Doggcatcher is my new postcast client. I bought it a week ago after the announcement that Google Listen was no longer being developed, and so far I'm very happy with it.  I tried switching to BeyondPod last year, but ended up being really disappointed by it and going back to Listen. I had previously avoided Doggcatcher because there is no free version or trial version, but after having used it for a while, I'd say it's definitely worth putting down the $5.  The UI is very polished, it's decently configurable, it allows me to set priorities on which podcasts I want to listen to first, and best of all it's much more responsive to the buttons on my Bluetooth headset than Listen was. In particular, I can disconnect the headset, then reconnect it, then press play, and it will pick up where it left off. Listen always required re-opening the app after the headset reconnected in order for the buttons to work again.

I went to their site - signed up for their forums and posted my problem.  One user replied and said he thought it must be a problem with Android.  Sorry, but no.  It used to work fine.  And that's the kind of reply developers use when they have absolutely no idea what's wrong with their application. If I can't use it with Bluetooth - I can't use it at all because my bluetooth headset is what I use to make phone calls and listen to audio from the phone.
